SIMPLE: familiar
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Familiar
<hw>Fa*mil`iar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>familer</ets>, <ets>familier</ets>, F. <ets>familier</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>familiaris</ets>, fr. <ets>familia</ets> family. See
<er>Family</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a family;
domestic.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Familiar</xex> feuds.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> familial.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Closely acquainted or intimate, as a friend or
companion; well versed in, as any subject of study; <as>as,
<ex>familiar</ex> with the Scriptures</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by, or exhibiting, the manner of an
intimate friend; not formal; unconstrained; easy; accessible.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In loose, <xex>familiar</xex> strains.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be thou <qex>familiar</qex>, but by no means vulgar.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Well known; well understood; common; frequent;
<as>as, a <ex>familiar</ex> illustration</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That war, or peace, or both at once, may be⟦br⟧
As things acquainted and <qex>familiar</qex> to us.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is nothing more <qex>familiar</qex> than this.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Improperly acquainted; wrongly intimate.</def>
<rj><au>Camden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Familiar spirit</b></col>, <cd>a demon or evil spirit
supposed to attend at call.</cd> <rj><au>1 Sam. xxviii. 3,
7-9.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Familiar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Familiar
<hw>Fa*mil"iar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An intimate; a
companion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All my <qex>familiars</qex> watched for my halting.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. xx. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An attendant demon or evil spirit.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Court of Inquisition)</fld> <def>A confidential
officer employed in the service of the tribunal, especially in
apprehending and imprisoning the accused.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>familiarise</ent>⟦br⟧
